Data Pre-Processing and Exploratory Analysis¶

All coding, write up and analysis in this Jupyter Notebook was done by Awad Abdelhalim.¶

Work prior to this notebook:¶

  • Original crash dataset was obtained from VDot SmarterRoads portal.
    • The dataset consisted of two files of relevance: 1) Virginia_Crashes.dbf (1.24 GB) 2) Viriniga_Crashes.shp (22 MB).
  • The raw data from the dbf file was converted into cvs format to compress information into 217 MBs.
  • A brief statistical analysis was carried out on the file using SAS JMP software, results are briefly discussed in the project report.
  • Inorder to reduce the size of the datafile prior to work in this notebook and upcoming notebooks, a few auxiliary attributes (crash ID, accident document number etc..) were removed, and all categorical information was label encoded into integers, the final Virginia_Crashes.csv file was also combined with location data for each accident extracted from the .shp file. Virginia_Crashes.csv is included with this report.
  • CheatSheet.xlsx shows describtion of each attribute overall and label encoding for each attribute.

Train-Test Split¶

We're tyring to see if we can predict crash severity based conditions prior to the accident. Those pre-accident conditions are defined by the attributes of

  • Data from the imported dataframe was extracted into numpy arrays, which were broken down into training and testing sets.
  • X contains the attributes and Y contains the respective labels we're trying to predict which is crash severity.
  • Majority of accidents in the dataset are severity 5: Property Damage accidents, the number of severity 1 (Fatal) and 3 (Pedestrian Fatal) is scarce, hence stratified sampling was used when breaking down the data to ensure we don't end up with training or test sets what do not include samples from such accidents.

Ensemble Method¶

Random Forest Classifier¶

A random forest classifier was used to predict crash severity. Per Wikipedia, " Random forests or random decision forests are an ensemble learning method for classification, regression and other tasks, that operate by constructing a multitude of decision trees at training time and outputting the class that is the mode of the classes (classification) or mean prediction (regression) of the individual trees. Random decision forests correct for decision trees' habit of overfitting to their training set ".

Data was originally trained and tested on classifier with 100 estimators.¶

The number of estimators (sub-trees) was reduced to 20 in this notebook to reduce computational time for reviewer.¶

Remove property damage crashes¶

Property damage crashes (Severity_5) are extremely unpredictable under any circumstances and make up a massive fraction of the data, yet they hinder prediction of other classes. In the following part of this notebook we remove those records as we are only interested in being able to predict crashes that lead to injuries and fatalities.

Accuracy is misguiding!¶

The classifier looked to have very high accuracy after removing the noisy property damage crashes. However, the reason for this turns out to be that it is misclassifying accident categories 1, 3 & 4 (respectively fatal, pedestrian fatal and pedestrian injury) crashes into severity category 2 (injury crashes). This is because as was shown above, the majority of the data is injury crashes and thus far we've given everything the same weight.

Penalize misclassifying fatal crashes¶

To overcome this bias, we give each class a weight equal to the inverse of it's fraction (i.e 1/[(sum xi/n)])

Stochastic Gradient Descent¶

We see that when giving each class an appropriate weight to make for the dataset bias, the classifier accuracy drops drastically. This is expected as accidents are extremely stochastic and aren't expected to be predicted easily.

Next, we use a Stochastic Gradient Descent classifier, which in addition to using the class weights we have used above also uses a loss function to penalize for misclassification. The SDG Classifier applied uses mini-batching (breaks dataset into epochs) and an adaptive learning rate function. While much better accuracy is expected using a customized loss function or optimizing class weights, this is out of scope of this project.

Data was originally trained and tested on classifier with 500 max_iterations.¶

The number of iterations was reduced to 20 in this notebook to reduce computational time for reviewer.¶

In [19]:

                           eta0= 0.03, learning_rate='invscaling', class_weight= w)

Noticeable Improvement¶

The SDG Classification offers significant improvement over classification tree methods by using the loss function which penalizes misclassification. The basic SGD implemented managed to correctly predict almost 50% of fatal accidents and a stagerring 68% of Pedestrian Fatal Accidents, which is very high considering the highly stochastic nature of the data.

Much better results are expected when optimizing this method for the dataset.¶

Concluding Remarks¶

The classification models explored above show potential for predicting accident severity based only on pre-accident conditions. In the following notebooks (and sections of the report), we explore dividing the multi-class classification task above into multiple binary classification problems using LightGradientBoosting. We also explore completely ignoring the severity and testing the dataset for association rules between different pre-accident conditions that may cause more accidents.

Data Visualization¶

In this section of the notebook, we explore innovative ways to analyze the dataset through visualization.¶

Two techniques were implemented:¶

  • Applying Principal Component Analyses to the dataset and reducing the attribute data to 3 dimensions which allows visualzing. The resulting 3D plot shows that certain accident severities seem to cluster together, but 3 components is definitely not enough to explain all the variance.

  • Next, KMeans clustering was applied to the geographical coordinates of the dataset. Virginia Department of Transportation (VDOT) currenlty operates through 9 different subdivisions (Districts), the purpose of this analyses was to visualize the crash clusters and test if that maps to district boundaries.

Crashes Geographical Clustering¶

KMeans clustering was used. The algorithm was initialized 100 different times with different centroid seeds for each of the 9 clusters. As per Sci-kit Learn documentation, "the final results will be the best output of n_init consecutive runs in terms of inertia".

Data was originally clustered on by KMeans with 100 centroid initializations.¶

The number of centroid initializations was reduced to 20 in this notebook to reduce computational time for reviewer.¶

So what if?¶

The KMeans clusters identified almost match with the geographical boundaries of the Virginia Department of Transportation Boundaries. So what if those administrative boundaries that VDOT executive offices control were re-drawn based on areas of accident frequency rather than geographical boundaries?
